{{No footnotes|date=June 2021}} '''Hando''' (犯土) is one of the [[selection days]] ({{ill|selection day|ja|選日|1=Senjitsu|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). Also referred to as '''Tsuchi''', '''Shii''', or '''Tsuchi'''.
From [[Kanoe-no-Uma]] ({{ill|Kanoe-no-Uma|ja|庚午|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the seventh day from {{ill|Kinoe-no-Ne|ja|甲子|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) to [[Hinoe-no-Ne]] ({{ill|Hinoe-no-Ne|ja|丙子|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the thirteenth day), the seven days are called '''Dai-Hando''' (大犯土, "Great Hando" or "Great Earth"). From [[Tsuchinoe-no-Tora]] ({{ill|Tsuchinoe-no-Tora|ja|戊寅|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the fifteenth day) to [[Kanoe-no-Saru]] ({{ill|Kanoe-no-Saru|ja|甲申|1=Yang Wood Monkey|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the twenty-first day), the seven days are called '''Sho-Hando''' (小犯土, "Small Hando" or "Small Earth"). The intervening day, [[Hinoe-no-Ushi]] ({{ill|Hinoe-no-Ushi|ja|丁丑|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the fourteenth day), is referred to as '''Kanbi''' (間日, "Intercalary Day"), '''Hando Kanbi''' (犯土間日, "Intercalary Hando Day"), or '''Chu-Hando''' (中犯土, "Middle Hando"). This day is excluded from the Hando period or, alternatively, included but without the taboos associated with Hando.
During the Hando periods, it is believed that the {{ill|Tsuchikami|ja|土公神|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Earth God) resides in their main shrine or within the earth, and thus the earth must not be disturbed. Activities such as digging, well-digging, sowing seeds, civil engineering works, and tree felling are all prohibited. Particularly for [[Jichinsai]] ({{ill|Jichinsai|ja|地鎮祭|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, ground-breaking ceremonies), Hando is considered an inauspicious time. These beliefs align closely with those associated with {{ill|Doyo|ja|土用|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
Originally, Hando referred to acts of "disturbing the earth," particularly rituals corresponding to modern-day Jichinsai. Over time, the term evolved to encompass the prohibitions and periods associated with these acts.
